09","1305–1345":"1305–1345","1313–1361":"1313–1361","18 Dec 1360":"18 December 1360","1330":"1330","1373":"1373","1362":"1362","1361":"1361","1383":"1383","1350":"1350","1360":"1360","1305":"1305","1337":"1337","1313":"1313","1401":"1401","1335":"1335","Abt 1355":"about 1355","1356":"1356","1345":"1345","Bet. 20 Mar 1345–1346":"from 20 March 1345 to 1346","1453":"1453","1343":"1343","1409":"1409","1419":"1419","Tattershall, Lincolnshire, England":"Tattershall, Lincolnshire, England","England":"England, United Kingdom","Saxlingham, Norfolk, England":"Saxlingham, Norfolk, England","Colne Engaine, Essex, England":"Colne Engaine, Essex, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"William","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Probably the most successful of all the Old French names of Germanic origin that were introduced to England by the Normans. It is derived from Germanic <i>wil</i> ‘will, desire’ + <i>helm</i> ‘helmet, protection’. The fact that it was borne by the Conqueror himself does not seem to have inhibited its favour with the ‘conquered’ population: in the first century after the Conquest it was the commonest male name of all, and not only among the Normans. In the later Middle Ages it was overtaken by   John  , but continued to run second to that name until the 20th century, when the picture became more fragmented."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":7,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When William Bernanke was born in 1330, in Saxlingham, Norfolk, England, his father, John Bernanke, was 25 and his mother, Joan de Marmion, was 17. He married Mary Engaine about 1355, in Colne Engaine, Essex, England, United Kingdom. They w